            <h2>üöÄ Getting Started with Raw Feeding</h2>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <h3>What is raw feeding and why should I consider it for my pet?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>Raw feeding, also known as BARF (Biologically Appropriate Raw Food), involves feeding your pet uncooked, natural ingredients that mirror what they would eat in the wild. This includes muscle meat, organ meat, and bones.</p>
                    <p>Benefits include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Improved dental health and fresher breath</li>
                        <li>Shinier coat and healthier skin</li>
                        <li>Better digestion and smaller, firmer stools</li>
                        <li>Increased energy levels</li>
                        <li>Reduced allergies and food sensitivities</li>
                        <li>Better weight management</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <h3>How much does it cost to feed raw compared to commercial pet food?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p>While the upfront cost may seem higher, many pet owners find raw feeding comparable or even cheaper long-term when considering:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reduced vet bills due to better health</li>
                        <li>Smaller portion sizes needed (higher bioavailability)</li>
                        <li>No need for expensive supplements</li>
                        <li>Buying in bulk and seasonal sales</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>On average, raw feeding costs ¬£2-4 per day for a medium-sized dog, compared to ¬£1.50-5 for premium commercial food.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-question">
                    <h3>What's the difference between complete meals and individual ingredients?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <p><strong>Complete meals</strong> are pre-balanced combinations that include the proper ratios of muscle meat, organ meat, and bone. These are perfect for beginners or busy pet owners.</p>
                    <p><strong>Individual ingredients</strong> allow you to create custom meals but require knowledge of proper ratios (80% muscle meat, 10% organ meat, 10% edible bones).</p>
                    <p>We recommend starting with complete meals and gradually learning to balance your own recipes.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-section" data-category="safety">
